<LEADPARA>  The Texas Senate, on a 29-2 vote Thursday, approved and sent to the House a
bill to make the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday a state holiday.;   
The bill by Sen. Frank Tejeda, D-San Antonio, also would move Confederate
Heroes Day -- honoring Jefferson Davis and Robert E. Lee -- from Jan. 19 to
June 3 and make it an optional holiday.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TEXAS SENATE OKS KING'S BIRTHDAY AS STATE
HOLIDAY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Under the measure, King's birthday would be celebrated on the third Monday
of January, to coincide with a national holiday in honor of the Nobel Peace
Prize winner and civil-rights leader. King was born Jan. 15, 1929, and was
assassinated April 4, 1968.;    "I'm just hopeful the House will also base
their vote on the merits of the bill, and on the greatness and achievement of
Martin Luther King, and not anything else," Tejeda said.;    Last month, a San
Antonio civil-rights group said it would ask the National Football League to
boycott Houston as a possible site for the 1995 Super Bowl unless Texas has a
full holiday for King. Tejeda said he would support a boycott.;    NFL
officials have said the status of a holiday for King is not among the criteria
to pick a Super Bowl site. But NFL owners recently stripped Phoenix of the
1993 Super Bowl after Arizona voters rejected a referendum to make King's
birthday a holiday.;    Under Tejeda's bill, employees would be entitled to be
off on King's birthday.;    Currently, state employees in Texas can take off
King's birthday only if they work another holiday.  </TEXT>
