<HEAD>Official King Holiday Wins Final Legislative Approval In Idaho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB FICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation declaring the third Monday in
January an official state holiday honoring Martin Luther King Jr.
won final legislative approval today.
   Senate passage of the bill establishing the Martin Luther King
Jr.-Idaho Human Rights Day removed Idaho from the dwindling list of
states still refusing to honor the slain civil rights leader with
an official holiday.
   The bill, clearing the Senate on a 28-11 vote, now goes to Gov.
Cecil Andrus, who called for its passage in his State of the State
address to open the session last January.
   ``We've come a long way down the road,'' said Sen. Mary Lou
Reed, a Democrat, citing the past four years since the state
designated the third Monday in January as a commemorative day for
King.
   Only three other states are now without King holidays _ Montana,
New Hampshire and Arizona.
   The Idaho measure, however, faced a somewhat rocky road in a
Legislature that has passed some of the toughest anti-racism laws
in the nation, including a criminal malicious harassment law and
mandatory hate-crime reporting.
   After winning initial Senate passage, it was sidetracked in the
House until a compromise was agreed to on the formal name. The
agreement added Idaho Human Rights Day to the designation.
   The holiday was pushed by lawmakers and the governor in part to
offset the negative image the state has developed because of the
presence of white supremacists at the Aryan Nations compound of
Richard Butler in northern Idaho.
   But now with the new holiday and the laws enacted in past
sessions, Mrs. Reed said, ``We have the finest package of human
rights legislation in the nation.
   ``Richard Butler and his small band is just a pitiful bunch,''
she said. ``The Aryan Nations people are now moving into the states
of Wyoming and Montana.''
   The major opposition focused on the potential cost of another
day off for government workers, estimated anywhere between $100,000
and $2 million depending on whether payroll is considered, and
King's radical political background.
   Andrus said, however, that ``more than a holiday to honor one
man, it will be a day to honor all like him, who believe that no
person can truly be free when even one other person is denied
liberty.''

</TEXT>
