<HEAD>Idaho Legislature Approves King Holiday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK WARBIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holiday honoring Martin Luther King Jr.
won final approval in the Legislature on Friday, making Idaho the
47th state agreeing to adopt the federal holiday.
   Senate passage of the measure on a 28-11 vote assured it of
becoming law with Gov. Cecil Andrus' promised approval.
   The vote was one of the Legislature's last acts before
adjourning for the year, and came four years after the state
designated the third Monday in January as a commemorative day but
not an official holiday for King.
   Arizona, New Hampshire and Montana also have refused to
designate a holiday.
   ``We've come a long way down the road,'' Sen. Mary Lou Reed
said. ``We have the finest package of human rights legislation in
the nation.''
   The Legislature has passed some of the toughest laws in the
nation against racial harassment and discrimination. But the King
holiday, after winning initial Senate passage, was sidetracked in
the House.
   Final passage came when the Senate agreed to a House amendment
to call the holiday Martin Luther King Jr.-Idaho Human Rights Day.
   A black community leader, the Rev. Ellis Robinson of St. Paul
Baptist Church in Boise, said the action extended the holiday
beyond King to ``anyone who's ever struggled and worked for the
rights of others.''
   ``We're not looking at this as a victory for black people,''
Robinson said. ``We're looking at it as a victory for all people.''
   The King holiday was pushed by lawmakers and the governor in
part to offset the negative image the state has developed because
of the presence of white supremacists at the Aryan Nations compound
of Richard Butler in the state's panhandle.
   The major opposition focused on the potential cost of another
day off for government workers, estimated anywhere between $100,000
and $2 million, depending on whether payroll is considered.
</TEXT>
